sMobile\" data-target=\"#feedbackModal_main_2534408\" data-toggle=\"modal\" role=\"button\" tabindex=\"0\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"ico-feedback\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-feedback\"></use></svg><span class=\"zDocsFeedbackButtonText\"> Feedback</span></span></div></div><div class=\"zDocsTopicActionsMobile\"><button aria-label=\"Show topic actions\" data-toggle=\"dropdown\" id=\"zDocsTopicActionsMobile\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"ico-ellipsis-h\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-ellipsis-h\"></use></svg></button><div class=\"dropdown-menu zDocsDropdownMenu zDocsTopicActionsMobileDropdown dropdown-menu-right\"></div></div><div style=\"flex-basis: 100%; height: 0px;\"></div><ul class=\"zDocsTopicPageDetails\"><li class=\"zDocsTopicPageDate css-cinqea\">Last Updated<span class=\"css-cinqea\">Sept 08, 2024</span></li><li class=\"zDocsAiTopicSummaryDetailsItem\"><button class=\"zDocsAiTopicSummaryButton\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"ico-topic-summary\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-topic-summary\"></use></svg>Summarize</button></li><li class=\"spacer\" role=\"presentation\"></li><div class=\"zDocsLabelWrapper\"><ul><li class=\"zDocsLabel\"><a aria-describedby=\"hyperLinkFacetsTooltip\" class=\"css-ettsdk\" data-tooltip-content=\"Search all site by tag: Uniface\" data-tooltip-id=\"hyperLinkFacetsTooltip\" href=\"/de-DE/search?labelkey=prod_uniface\" stylesprops=\"[object Object]\"><svg aria-label=\"Tag\" class=\"ico-tag\" role=\"img\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-tag\"></use></svg>Uniface</a></li><li class=\"zDocsLabel\"><a aria-describedby=\"hyperLinkFacetsTooltip\" class=\"css-ettsdk\" data-tooltip-content=\"Search all site by tag: 10.4\" data-tooltip-id=\"hyperLinkFacetsTooltip\" href=\"/de-DE/search?labelkey=uniface_10.4\" stylesprops=\"[object Object]\"><svg aria-label=\"Tag\" class=\"ico-tag\" role=\"img\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-tag\"></use></svg>10.4</a></li></ul></div></ul></header><div class=\"zDocsTopicPageBody\" data-prismjs-copy=\"Copy\" data-prismjs-copy-error=\"Copy failed! Use Ctrl + C instead.\" data-prismjs-copy-success=\"Copied!\"><div class=\"zDocsTopicPageBodyContent\" dir=\"ltr\"><div id=\"zDocsAiSummaryContaineruniface_104zdz1665702548111.html\"></div><div><article class=\"hascomments\" data-page=\"bundle:uniface_104/enus/zdz1665702548111.html\" id=\"bundle:uniface_104/enus/zdz1665702548111.html\"><main role=\"main\"><article aria-labelledby=\"ariaid-title1\" class=\"dita\" id=\"zdz1665702548111\" role=\"article\">\n<h1 class=\"title topictitle1\" id=\"ariaid-title1\">\n                       \n Certificate-Based Authentication\n   </h1>\n<div class=\"body conbody\" id=\"zdz1665702548111__certificate_based_authentication_106368\"><p class=\"shortdesc\">When TLS is configured for certificate-based authentication, it uses signed certificates to guarantee the identity of communicating peers, and a negotiated master key for encrypting and decrypting the data. The certificate and its associated key make it possible to support a wide range of encryption ciphers.\n </p>\n<p class=\"p\" id=\"zdz1665702548111__p_d32690e1_d32691e1_d32692e1\">When correctly configured, certificates provide much better security than pre-shared keys.</p>\n<p class=\"p\" id=\"zdz1665702548111__p_d32693e1_d32694e1_d32695e1\">You can create your own certificates or purchase certificates from a Certificate Authority (CA). When creating your own certificates, you can use simple self-signed certificates or you can act as CA yourself and issue certificates for your own use.</p>\n<p class=\"p\" id=\"zdz1665702548111__p_d32696e1_d32697e1_d32698e1\">To enable certificate-based encryption, configure the TLS connector for server verification using the <span class=\"keyword cmdname\">verify_server</span> connector option. Optionally, you can configure client verification using the <span class=\"keyword cmdname\">verify_client</span> connector option.</p>\n<p class=\"p\" id=\"zdz1665702548111__p_d32699e1_d32700e1_d32701e1\">For more information, see <a class=\"xref\" data-bundleid=\"uniface_104\" data-navpath=\"trs1665702548192.html\" href=\"/de-DE/bundle/uniface_104/page/trs1665702548192.html\" title=\"To configure the TLS connector to use certificates to secure the connection and encrypt the data, you must enable server verification. If required, you can also enable client verification.\">Configure the TLS Connector to Use Certificates</a>.</p>\n<div class=\"note note note_note\" id=\"zdz1665702548111__note_w7155ab1b5c11_w7156ab1b5_w7157ab1\"><span class=\"note__title\">Note:</span> All certificates and keys must be in PEM format.</div>\n</div>\n</article></main></article>\n</div></div><div class=\"contentPlaceholder\" style=\"height: 500px;\"><div class=\"contentContainer zDocsSideBoxes\"><div><h5 aria-level=\"5\" class=\"css-g931ng\">Related Links</h5><ul><li><a class=\"css-ettsdk\" href=\"/de-DE/bundle/uniface_104/page/fer1665702676920.html\" stylesprops=\"[object Object]\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"ico-related-link\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-related-link\"></use></svg>Digital Certificates</a><p>A digital certificate (also known as a public key certificate) is a digitally-signed document used to validate the identity of the sender in communication between a client and server.</p></li><li><a class=\"css-ettsdk\" href=\"/de-DE/bundle/uniface_104/page/pen1665702739479.html\" stylesprops=\"[object Object]\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"ico-related-link\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-related-link\"></use></svg>Creating Certificates</a><p>You can use tools such as OpenSSL to create certificates and generate RSA private and public keys for signature signing and verification. A self-signed TLS/SSL certificate is not signed by a publicly trusted certificate authority (CA) but instead by the developer or company that is responsible for the website; as a publicly trusted CA does not sign them, they are usually considered unsafe for public applications and websites.</p></li><li><a class=\"css-ettsdk\" href=\"/de-DE/bundle/uniface_104/page/bwg1665702724189.html\" stylesprops=\"[object Object]\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"ico-related-link\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-related-link\"></use></svg>Ciphers Supported by the TLS Connector</a><p>OpenSSL (which is used by the TLS connector) supports over 135 ciphers that can potentially be used with certificates.</p></li><li><a class=\"css-ettsdk\" href=\"/de-DE/bundle/uniface_104/page/ngj1665702888955.html\" stylesprops=\"[object Object]\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"ico-related-link\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-related-link\"></use></svg>verify_client</a><p>Determines whether a TLS client's certificate will be verified. The default is no.</p></li><li><a class=\"css-ettsdk\" href=\"/de-DE/bundle/uniface_104/page/fum1665702526378.html\" stylesprops=\"[object Object]\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"ico-related-link\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-related-link\"></use></svg>verify_server</a><p>Determines whether a TLS server's certificate will be verified. The default is no.</p></li></ul></div></div></div></div><div class=\"bottomFeedback\"><div aria-labelledby=\"bottomFeedbackText\" class=\"bottomFeedbackContent\" role=\"group\"><span class=\"bottomFeedbackText\" id=\"bottomFeedbackText\">Was this topic helpful?</span><div class=\"bottomFeedbackButtonGroup\"><a data-backdrop=\"static\" data-target=\"#feedbackModal_bottom_2534408\" data-toggle=\"modal\" href=\"#\" role=\"button\" type=\"button\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"ico-thumbs-up\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-thumbs-up\"></use></svg><span>Like</span></a><a data-backdrop=\"static\" data-target=\"#feedbackModal_bottom_2534408\" data-toggle=\"modal\" href=\"#\" role=\"button\" type=\"button\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"ico-thumbs-down\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-thumbs-down\"></use></svg><span>Dislike</span></a></div></div></div><div style=\"position: fixed; bottom: 170px; right: 70px; cursor: pointer; transition-duration: 0.2s; transition-timing-function: linear; transition-delay: 0s; z-index: 3; opacity: 0; visibility: hidden; transition-property: opacity, visibility;\"><button aria-label=\"Scroll to top\" class=\"zDocsScrollTopBtn\" data-tooltip-content=\"Scroll to top\" data-tooltip-id=\"zDocsBackToTopToolTip\" id=\"zDocsScrollToTop\" type=\"button\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"ico-next\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-next\"></use></svg></button></div></body></html>", "text": "Certificate-Based Authentication Add to My Topics Add selected topic and subtopics Add Topic & Subtopics with topic head Add entire publication Watch Download PDF Save selected topic Save selected topic and subtopics Save entire publication Share Email Link Copy Link Feedback Last Updated Sept 08, 2024 Summarize Uniface 10.4 Certificate-Based Authentication When TLS is configured for certificate-based authentication, it uses signed certificates to guarantee the identity of communicating peers, and a negotiated master key for encrypting and decrypting the data. The certificate and its associated key make it possible to support a wide range of encryption ciphers. When correctly configured, certificates provide much better security than pre-shared keys. You can create your own certificates or purchase certificates from a Certificate Authority (CA). When creating your own certificates, you can use simple self-signed certificates or you can act as CA yourself and issue certificates for your own use. To enable certificate-based encryption, configure the TLS connector for server verification using the verify_server connector option. Optionally, you can configure client verification using the verify_client connector option. For more information, see Configure the TLS Connector to Use Certificates . Note: All certificates and keys must be in PEM format. Related Links Digital Certificates A digital certificate (also known as a public key certificate) is a digitally-signed document used to validate the identity of the sender in communication between a client and server. Creating Certificates You can use tools such as OpenSSL to create certificates and generate RSA private and public keys for signature signing and verification. A self-signed TLS/SSL certificate is not signed by a publicly trusted certificate authority (CA) but instead by the developer or company that is responsible for the website; as a publicly trusted CA does not sign them, they are usually considered unsafe for public applications and websites. Ciphers Supported by the TLS Connector OpenSSL (which is used by the TLS connector) supports over 135 ciphers that can potentially be used with certificates. verify_client Determines whether a TLS client's certificate will be verified. The default is no. verify_server Determines whether a TLS server's certificate will be verified. The default is no. Was this topic helpful? Like Dislike"}